WEBVTT

00:00:00.720 --> 00:00:01.553
<v Instructor>Now let's talk</v>

00:00:01.553 --> 00:00:03.580
about Amazon Elastic Transcoder.

00:00:03.580 --> 00:00:06.280
So Elastic Transcoder is used to convert media files stored

00:00:06.280 --> 00:00:08.970
in Amazon S3 into media files in the format required

00:00:08.970 --> 00:00:11.570
by consumer playback devices, so phones, et cetera.

00:00:11.570 --> 00:00:13.300
So let's take a concrete example.

00:00:13.300 --> 00:00:14.660
You're going to put a media file,

00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:18.000
so, for example, a video, into your Amazon S3 buckets,

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:19.440
and then you're going to run it

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:22.460
through your transcoding pipeline on Elastic Transcoder,

00:00:22.460 --> 00:00:25.090
and it's going to convert that video file into a bunch

00:00:25.090 --> 00:00:27.400
of different video files that are all going to be put

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:29.690
into an S3 output bucket.

00:00:29.690 --> 00:00:31.920
And that output bucket is going to have a bunch

00:00:31.920 --> 00:00:34.480
of files that are going to be compatible with a wide array

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:36.650
of different devices, such as your smartphones

00:00:36.650 --> 00:00:39.030
your tablets, your PC, et cetera, et cetera.

00:00:39.030 --> 00:00:41.170
So the benefits of using Elastic Transcoder

00:00:41.170 --> 00:00:42.490
is that it's easy to use.

00:00:42.490 --> 00:00:44.970
It's highly scalable, so the more files you have

00:00:44.970 --> 00:00:46.600
in your N3 output bucket,

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:48.900
the more processing power that you're going to have.

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:51.180
It's cost effective because you're only going to pay

00:00:51.180 --> 00:00:54.140
for the amount of time that your media was being transcoded,

00:00:54.140 --> 00:00:55.750
and it's fully managed and secure.

00:00:55.750 --> 00:00:57.310
You're only going to pay for what you use.

00:00:57.310 --> 00:00:58.600
So the idea is that, yes,

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:00.640
it's perfect use case for the cloud.

00:01:00.640 --> 00:01:02.860
So you don't need to spend money and money

00:01:02.860 --> 00:01:05.700
on your EC2 instances to convert your files.

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:07.250
You can just use Elastic Transcoder

00:01:07.250 --> 00:01:09.540
and just pay what has been consumed.

00:01:09.540 --> 00:01:10.860
So I hope you liked this lecture.

00:01:10.860 --> 00:01:12.610
I will see you in the next lecture.